occurrences.line_text: To seeke her Knight, as Talus her did guide:
And comming down to seeke them, where they wond,
And gan for grace and loue of her to seeke:
I will not seeke the same from you to hide,
To seeke her loue, where he was to be sought;
To seeke for succour of her and of her Peares
To seeke for succour of this Ladies gieft:
That it was she, the which for helpe did seeke.
More then his loue, which thus ye seeke t'obtaine.
For his sicke charge some harbour there to seeke;
To seeke, if he perchance a sleepe were layd,
To seeke some comfort in that sorie case.
But of them all, which did his ruine seeke
To seeke some place, the which mote yeeld some ease
If therefore health ye seeke, obserue this one.
Like scattred sheepe, to seeke for safetie,
He would surceasse, but him, where so he were, would seeke.
To seeke for safety, which long time she sought:
To seeke for booty, came by fortune blynde,
As he to seeke Serena through the woods did roue.
And seeke to please, that now is counted wisemens threasure.
He seekes out mighty charmes, to trouble sleepy mindes
Forsaken Truth long seekes her loue,
In vaine he seekes that hauing cannot hold.
He seekes, of all his drift the aymed end:
Who seekes with painfull toile, shall honour soonest find.
In vaine seekes wonders out of Magicke spell.
Vaine is the art that seekes it selfe for to deceiue.
That seekes to know anothers griefe in vaine,
who seekes her to entrap.
Seekes to subuert her Crowne and dignity,
But that he seekes by traytrous traines to spill
That seekes to saue the subiect of her skill,
The stubborne mettall seeketh to subdew,
In vaine he seeketh others to suppresse,
Still seeking him, that from her still did flie,
Seeking for daunger and aduentures vaine?
As seeking medicine, whence she was stong,
From seeking praise, and deeds of armes abrode,
Seeking the weake oppressed to relieue,
Seeking aduentures hard, to exercise
And Penda, seeking him adowne to tread,
Seeking to match the chaste with th'vnchaste Ladies traine.
Which after rest they seeking far abrode,
Seeking aduentures in the saluage wood,
Seeking aduentures, where they anie knew.
The which in seeking for her children three
In seeking him, that should her paine assoyle;
Seeking aduentures, where he mote heare tell;
Him seeking euermore, yet no where him descride.
And seeking long, to weet which way she straid
Whom seeking euer since with endlesse paines,
And seeking often entraunce, afterwards in vaine.
By all meanes seeking to asswage their ires,
From seeking fauour, where it doth abound;
For seeking thus to salue the Amazon,
Now seeking darkenesse, and now seeking light;
Now seeking darkenesse, and now seeking light;
By change of place seeking to ease her paine;
Seeking by euery way to make some breach,
Seeking to driue away deepe rooted dreede,
In seeking all the woods both farre and nye
Find remedie vnsought, which seeking cannot fynd.
And seeking all things meete for remedy.
Of Calidore; who seeking all this while
And falsly seekst a vertuous wight to shame?
The caruer Holme, the Maple seeldom inward sound.
Brayes out her latest breath, and vp her eyes doth seele.
But seeled vp with death, shall haue their deadly meed.
A seely Lambe farre from the flocke does take,
Come, come away, fraile, seely, fleshly wight,
The seely man seeing him ryde so rancke,
Me seely wretch she so at vauntage caught,
Full iolly knight he seemd, and faire did sitt,
That lasie seemd in being euer last,
Seemd in their song to scorne the cruell sky.
That path they take, that beaten seemd most bare,
Her swollen hart her speach seemd to bereaue,
Not all content, yet seemd she to appease
His louely words her seemd due recompence
And eke th'enchaunter ioyous seemd no lesse,
The house of mightie Prince it seemd to bee:
That seemd as fresh as Flora in her prime,
Whose fellowship seemd far vnfit for warlike swaine.
He seemd in hart to harbour thoughts vnkind,
For feare as seemd, or for some feigned losse;
That all the earth for terrour seemd to shake,
That with his talnesse seemd to threat the skye,
Close couched on the beuer, seem'd to throw
Did shake, and seem'd to daunce for iollity,
But all that was not such, as seemd in sight,
And seem'd himselfe as conquered to yield.
Such was this Gyaunts fall, that seemd to shake
That of him selfe he seemd to be afrayd;
And foltring tongue at last these words seemd forth to shake.
Panthea, seemd the brightest thing, that was:
And seemd vneath to shake the stedfast ground.
That nothing seemd the puissance could withstand:
As hundred ramping Lyons seem'd to rore,
So huge and horrible a masse it seem'd;
That seemd like silke and siluer wouen neare,
He seemd to be a sage and sober sire,
Full loth she seemd thereto, but yet did faine;
That seemd her tender heart was rent in twaine,
Seemd to haue beene a goodly personage,
That all his senses seemd bereft attone:
Seemd that lowde thunder with amazement great
Therewith all suddeinly he seemd enraged,
That seemd to be a woman of great worth,
A siluer sound, that heauenly musicke seemd to make.
She seemd, when she presented was to sight,
Yet seemd no lesse to loue, then loued to bee:
That seemd him to enflame on euery side:
Him deeming dead, as then he seemd in sight,
That nothing seem'd mote beare so monstrous might:
The frame thereof seemd partly circulare,
That mad or foolish seemd: one by his vew
A bridge of bras, whose sound heaue[n]s thunder seem'd to bee.
As euery one seem'd meetest in that cace.
That like a ghost he seem'd, whose graue-clothes were vnbound.
That seem'd to tremble euermore, and quake:
Made of a dead mans skull, that seem'd a ghastly sight.
Some land-marke seem'd to be, or signe of sundry way.
That could not die, yet seem'd a mortall wight,
That seem'd more horrible then hell to bee,
Which seemd so sweet and pleasant to the eye,
Which seem'd to fly for feare, them to behold:
And this great Vniuerse seemd one confused mas.
That seemd a worke of admirable wit;
That seemd the waues were into yuory,
Yt seemd th'enchaunted flame, which did CreÃ¼sa wed.
That trauellers to him seemd to entize;
And garments loose, that seemd vnmeet for womanhed.
Of which some seemd with liuely iollitee,
Which drops of Christall seemd for wantones to weepe.
That like a little lake it seemd to bee;
That seemd the fountaine in that sea did sayle vpright.
The young man sleeping by her, seemd to bee
That seem'd to couch vnder his shield three-square,
That seem'd both shield & plate it would haue riued;
Full griesly seem'd: therein they long did ryde,
She seemd a woman of great bountihed,
But fierce Bacchante seemd too fell and keene;
Faire Lady she him seemd, like Lady drest,
Like to the world it selfe, and seem'd a world of glas.
And all his armour seem'd of antique mould,
Thrice shined faire, and thrice seem'd dim and wan,
His steed eke seem'd t'apply his steps to his intent.
Emongst the pumy stones, which seemd to plaine
That all the rest it seem'd they robbed bare
That seem'd the Ocean could not containe them there.
Busie (as seem'd) about some wicked gin:
That like a liuely sanguine it seem'd to the eye.
Who seem'd for feare to quake in euery lim,
He it dissembled well, and light seem'd to esteeme.
Gan greatly chaunge, and seem'd dismayd to bee;
And seem'd more grieuous, then it was before:
That seem'd no helpe for him was left in liuing sight.
Straunge thing it seem'd, that none was to possesse
As those same plumes, so seemd he vaine and light,
Who seemd of riper yeares, then th'other Swaine,
That euill matched paire they seemd to bee:
So seemd those two, as growne together quite,
That seem'd full hard t'accord two things so far in dout.
Perceiu'd to be such as they seemd in vew,
And prou'd himselfe most foole, in what he seem'd most wise.
Combing her golden lockes, as seemd her good:
And eke so short, that seemd their ends out shortly came.
More happie creatures, then they seem'd to bee,
And each to other seemd the victorie to yield.
That life it selfe seemd loathsome, and long safetie ill.
That seemd some perilous tumult to desine,
That toward them his course seem'd to apply,
Them seemd, that could so goodly riches gaine,
She seem'd to passe: so forged things do fairest shew.
That dreadfull seem'd to euery liuing wight,
He like a monstrous Gyant seem'd in sight,
That seem'd to dust he shortly would it driue:
That seem'd a rocke of Diamond it could riue,
Where better seem'd he mote himselfe repose;
So euery place seem'd painefull, and ech changing vaine.
That seem'd he was full bent to some mischieuous deede.
The feare whereof seem'd much her to affray:
The place there ouerflowne, seemd like a sodaine flood.
In saluage chase, to rest as seem'd her meet.
That seem'd his shrikes would rend the brasen skie:
But that same dwarfe right sorie seem'd and sad,
With murmure soft, that seem'd to serue the workmans will.
It seem'd a second paradise to ghesse,
That seem'd to be of very sober mood,
Whose shapes seem'd not like to terrestriall boyes,
For sacrilege me seem'd the Church to rob,
And folly seem'd to leaue the thing vndonne,
Yet seem'd full aged by his outward sight,
And eke he somewhat seem'd to stoupe afore
That seem'd like siluer, sprinckled here and theare
It was no mortall worke, that seem'd and yet was not.
That seem'd vnlike vnto his earthly home:
That nothing like himselfe he seem'd in sight.
For that to her he seem'd best skild in righteous lore.
He, whether mine seem'd fayrer in his eye,
As that it seem'd aboue the ground he went:
To see the thing, that seem'd so excellent,
Seem'd that for it these Squires at ods did fall,
Of which the one him seem'd a Knight all armed,
Well shot in yeares he seem'd, and rather bent
Her seem'd, as she was doing sacrifize
Seem'd to awake in horrible dismay,
Therefore thus one of them, who seem'd in sight
That deadly daunger seem'd in all mens sight,
That goodly seem'd t'adorne her royall state,
First gan he tell, how this that seem'd so faire
That seem'd their soules they wold haue ryuen quight
That seem'd a marble rocke asunder could haue riue.
And seem'd to be of infinite great strength;
Yet he past on, and seem'd of them to take no keepe.
That from the battlements she ready seem'd to fall.
Seem'd to be Calidore: all other helpes were past.
Seem'd not to weigh his threatfull words at all,
Him seem'd his feet did fly, and in their speed delight.
That rather seem'd the conquest of his might,
That seem'd the spoile of some right well renownd.
Seem'd like a groue faire braunched ouer hed:
For well it seem'd, that whilome he had beene
That quite they seem'd past helpe of surgery,
Seem'd vnder her protection him to shroud;
So different from that, which earst ye seem'd in sight?
That seem'd a marble pillour it could bow:
Yet seem'd the soyle both fayre and frutefull eft,
Of matchlesse hight, that seem'd th'earth to disdaine;
Seem'd all the rest in beauty to excell,
That two of them still fr[ow]ard seem'd to bee,
That seem'd to be some sorie simple clowne,
Whereof right glad they seem'd, and offer made
Sober he seemde, and very sagely sad,
Faire Venus seemde vnto his bed to bring
But now seemde best, the person to put on
Full iolly knight he seemde, and well addrest,
Both seemde to win, and both seemde won to bee,
Both seemde to win, and both seemde won to bee,
And euer false Duessa seemde as faire as shee.
But of his cheere did seeme too solemne sad;
Cast a blacke stole, most like to seeme for Vna fit.
For though a tree I seeme, yet cold and heat me paines.
But they did seeme more foule and hideous,
Ne dare to weepe, nor seeme to vnderstand
May seeme the wayne was very euill led,
I that do seeme not I, Duessa am,
To seeme like Truth, whose shape she well can faine,
Ne let it seeme, that credence this exceedes,
My loyalty, not such as it did seeme;
That strongest Oake might seeme to ouerthrow.
Did seeme to laugh on me, and fauour mine intent.
That signe of last outbreathed life did seeme,
Did seeme such, as she was, a goodly maiden Queene.
One that would wiser seeme, then all the rest,
His heart did seeme to melt in pleasures manifold.
Wherewith aboue all knights ye goodly seeme aguizd.
Ne ought would speake, but euermore did seeme
From which sad ruth does seeme you to restraine,
Which mariage make; that day too farre did seeme:
But whence should come that harme, which thou doest seeme
Thereby thine armes seeme stro[n]g, but manhood fraile;
Yet would not seeme so rude, and thewed ill,
His cole-blacke hands did seeme to haue beene seard
That heauy ruine they did seeme to threat;
Her face right wondrous faire did seeme to bee,
Yet gold all is not, that doth golden seeme,
For though they bodies seeme, yet substance from them fades.
That as a cloud doth seeme to dim the skies;
That not Scuith guiridh it mote seeme to bee
That all the seas for feare do seeme away to fly.
Yet well they seeme to him, that farre doth vew,
Which sparckling on the silent waues, does seeme more bright.
Whose face did seeme as cleare as Christall stone,
Things oft impossible (quoth she) seeme, ere begonne.
To order them, as best to thee doth seeme,
Deeme of her high desert, or seeme so light:
Miraculous may seeme to him, that reades
Which seeme to labour vnder their fruits lode:
Did seeme to be the same, which she escapt whyleare.
For both to be and seeme to him was labour lich.
But she, the more to seeme such as she hight,
That challenge did too peremptory seeme,
Is suffred here to enter, but he seeme
Nor seeme too suddeinly him to inuade:
Did liuely seeme to tremble, wheh she saw
So like, that all the walles did seeme to flame.
His sea-horses did seeme to sport amayne,
The God himselfe did pensiue seeme and sad,
Made him seeme happie for so glorious theft;
And makes it seeme to haue some other sourse:
And some that would seeme wise, their wonder turnd to dout.
But seeme gainst common sence to them most sweet;
The which did seeme vnto my simple doome,
But being faire and brickle, likest glasse did seeme.
The first of them did seeme of ryper yeares,
Albe they endlesse seeme in estimation,
And made it seeme to feele her grieuous paine,
For worthy thou of her doest rightly seeme.
Another that would seeme to haue more wit,
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
That what the sea vnto you sent, your own should seeme.
Doth seeme to be her selfe, though darkned be her light.
She told but moneths, to make them seeme more few:
Each hour did seeme a moneth, & euery moneth a yeare.
To so faire Ladie, as ye seeme in sight,
With her dull eyes did seeme to looke askew,
Of which though present age doe plenteous seeme,
The which did seeme a thousand tongues to haue,
But rather did more chearefull seeme therefore.
Faire Lady let it not you seeme disgrace,
That to all vertue it may seeme vnapt,
That mote to all men seeme an vncouth sight;
Much did the Crauen seeme to mone his case,
And standing on his tiptoes, to seeme tall,
Who on the other side did seeme so farre
Did seeme to ouerlooke the lowly vale;
Therefore they alwaies smoothly seeme to smile,
To make it seeme more deare and dainty, as is meet.
Seeme much more louely in that darknesse layd,
And some of Tygres, that did seeme to gren,
Seemed in heart some hidden care she had,
Then seemed him his Lady by him lay,
And eke the Graces seemed all to sing,
Much seemed he to mone her haplesse chaunce,
His looke was sterne, and seemed still to threat
Me seemed, by my side a royall Mayd
That seemed from some feared foe to fly,
Not all so chearefull seemed she of sight,
Me for to meet, that seemed ill bested,
Her face so faire as flesh it seemed not,
He saw from farre, or seemed for to see
Straunge seemed to the knight, that aye with foe
Who greatly ioyous seemed for my sake,
(That day it selfe him seemed all too long:)
That like a litle forrest seemed outwardly.
Yet seemed, nothing well they her became;
He seemed breathlesse, hartlesse, faint, and wan,
Ne of his safetie seemed care he kept,
Whose liues, it seemed, whilome there were shed,
But rather fowler seemed to the eye;
Tall yeomen seemed they, and of great might,
Another seemed enuious, or coy,
That chamber seemed ruinous and old,
In all that seemed fit for kingly seed:
As for her Syre and king her seemed best;
Seemed some great misfortune to deplore,
Whose bounches hanging downe, seemed to entice
Which therein bathing, seemed to contend,
Such seemed they, and so their yellow heare
There, whence that Musick seemed heard to bee,
For they all seemed curteous and gent,
High time it seemed then for euery wight
He met a Dwarfe, that seemed terrifyde
That seemed those two vertues stroue to find
That Geauntesse, is not such, as she seemed,
Or ill they seemed sure auizd to bee,
Being possessed of that spoyle, which seemed
Seemed to thunder, and did nigh affray
Mote not be entertaynd, as seemed meet,
So huge a scope at first him seemed best,
Him seemed more their manner did agree;
As seemed by their semblaunt did entreat;
To be a man, such as indeed he seemed,
Yet since he seemed valiant, through vnknowne,
For sure the fayrest Florimell him seemed,
He seemed brought to bed in Paradise,
Were sent, that seemed death in them to beare,
So fresh he seemed and so fierce in sight;
Then he halfe vanquisht, then the other seemed,
T'obey their riders hest, as seemed good.
And bright, that seemed borne of Angels brood,
For such an Hag, that seemed worse then nought,
Like as it seemed best to euery one;
As one that seemed doubtfull or dismayd.
With oaken leaues attrapt, that seemed fit
It seemed, him to terme the saluage knight.
For all afore that seemed fayre and bright,
That seemed some blacksmith dwelt in that desert grou[n]d.
That seemed nought but death mote be her destinie.
Him seemed oft he heard his owne right name.
That seemed nought the souse thereof could beare,
They saw together skirmishing, as seemed:
Full weake and crooked creature seemed she,
He wore, that seemed strange to common vew,
As sundry chaunge her seemed best to ease.
An hideous tempest seemed from below,
So there without the gate (as seemed best)
That seemed to outshine the dimmed skye,
Seemed those litle Angels did vphold
That seemed nought could him from death protect:
He burst into these words, as to him seemed good.
Nathelesse, sith ye so courteous seemed late,
Him they did deeme, as sure to them he seemed,
But first him seemed fit, that wounded Knight
A voice, that seemed of some woman kynd,
Which seemed by their portance and attire,
With so huge force, that seemed nothing might
As to them seemed fit time to entertaine.
To doe some thing, that seemed to him best,
For bootelesse thing him seemed, to abide
That seemed nought the course thereof could stay:
And markt her rare demeanure, which him seemed
Then Coridon woxe frollicke, that earst seemed dead.
Approcht, him seemed that the merry sound
With open mouth, that seemed to containe
That Artegall him selfe her seemelesse plight did rew.
So forth they rode, he feining seemely merth,
Faire seemely pleasaunce each to other makes,
Which doen, she vp arose with seemely grace,
And naked nature seemely to aray;
In seemely sort their corses to engraue,
And seemely welcome for her did prepare:
And with sad Cypresse seemely it embraue,
Seemely to entertaine her new-come guest,
Did order all th'Achates in seemely wise,
A seemely Maiden, sitting by the shore,
Dwelt simple truth in seemely fashion.
Yet in that horror shewd a seemely grace,
And her salewd with seemely belaccoyle,
Thus sate they all a round in seemely rate:
And them beside two seemely damzels stood,
In seemely wise, as them beseemed best:
In gentle thewes, and such like seemely leres.
But rather ioyd to be, then seemen sich:
Certes sir Knight[s], ye seemen much to blame,
Faire harbour that them seemes; so in they entred arre.
Sometimes Dame Venus selfe he seemes to see,
And said, Old sire, it seemes thou hast not red
And proue thy puissaunt armes, as seemes thee best became.
And now it seemes, that she suborned hath
And yet the stone her semblance seemes to show,
Seemes that through many yeares thy wits thee faile,
Seemes to be borne by natiue influence;
But chiefly skill to ride, seemes a science
And he that breathlesse seemes, shal corage bold respire.
It seemes, iust wrongs to vengeance doe prouoke,
That fairer seemes, the lesse ye see her may;
And certes seemes bestowed not amis:
That either seemes some cursed witches deed,
Whereof she seemes ashamed inwardly.
That one of th'old Heroes seemes to bee:
And safest seemes, him soonest doth amate,
Me seemes I see Amintas wretched fate,
And sooth it seemes they say: for he may not
That all the countrey seemes to be a Maine,
That seemes rough Masons hand with engines keene
As white seemes fairer, macht with blacke attone;
Well seemes t'exceede the powre of patience,
That it prodigious seemes in common peoples sight.
Certes me seemes bene not aduised well,
And he that happie seemes and least in payne,
That from his force seemes nought may it defend;
That well (me seemes) appeares, by that of late
For he me seemes most fit the faire to serue,
That rather seemes, sith knowen armes ye shonne.
The faire Poeana; who seemes outwardly
Me seemes the gentle hart should most assured bind.
Gainst which me seemes this war ye wrongfully haue wielded.
Daughter me seemes of double wrong ye plaine,
Me seemes the world is runne quite out of square,
In stead of right me seemes great wrong dost shew,
To her bespake; Sir Knight it seemes to me,
Alreadie seemes that fortunes headlong wheele
As by sad Belge seemes, whose wrongs though long
Of Court it seemes, men Courtesie doe call,
In whom it seemes, that gentlenesse of spright
My knight hers soone, as seemes, to daunger droue
Me seemes, that him befell by his owne fault:
Ill seemes (sayd he) if he so valiaunt be,
Such then (said Vna) as she seemeth here,
And seemeth safe from stormes, that may offend;
Faire Damzell, seemeth, by your troubled cheare,
The Prince him selfe halfe seemeth to offend,
Seemeth that such wild woods should far expell
That seemeth well to answere to your weede?
Strooke him, as seemeth, vnderneath the hart,
He started vp, as seeming to mistrust,
A seeming body of the subtile aire,
As many formes and shapes in seeming wise,
In so ritch weedes and seeming glorious show,
With chaunge of cheare the seeming simple maid
Now not a Lady, but a seeming tree;
Th'one seeming such, the other such indeede,
Her seeming dead he found with feigned feare,
By his like seeming shield, her knight by name
And false Duessa seeming Lady faire,
As ashes pale of hew and seeming ded;
And him amoues with speaches seeming fit:
That he his paine endur'd, as seeming now more light.
Who them requites with court'sies seeming meet,
With flying speede, and seeming great pretence,
Who seeming sorely chauffed at his band,
Through inward feare, and seeming pale and faint
And kindling new his courage seeming queint,
As to despise so courteous seeming part,
To wreake your wrath on this dead seeming knight,
Now seeming flaming whot, now stony cold.
And Hengist seeming sad, for that was donne,
